posts.name: SLAB-Mr.Thomas
posts.cooked:
I have many Time variables that ideally are in an array such as

This has compiler error Cannot create a generic array of Measure<Time> .

Is there syntax that comes close to this for my usage or would I have to make a double[100] and forget storing the Measure ?

posts.name: Fletch
posts.cooked: I don’t believe you can do native arrays of generic types like that.  You should be able to use any generic type though. ArrayList<Measure<Time>> would probably do what you need though

posts.name: SLAB-Mr.Thomas
posts.cooked:
Making the ArrayList does work and is close to an array but I don’t know how to fill the array list with a lot of Measure<Time> objects because the Measure<Time> cannot be instantiated. How do I mass produce 100 objects for the list? This doesn’t work:

Cannot instantiate the type Measure<Time>

This works but it isn’t the shortcut I’m looking for:

A possibility I’m not fond of is call a method 100 times that returns a Measure<Time> .

posts.name: Fletch
posts.cooked:
This is starting to feel like a bit of an XY Problem.

Perhaps you could explain what youre trying to do at a higher level.  Why do you need all the objects in the array pre-filled?

posts.name: Matt Soucy (he/him)
posts.cooked: In your “it works”, your time0 is actually initialized to null , not to a new object. You can’t create a new Measure<Time> because Measure is an interface - you need a class that implements Measure in order to instantiate it.

posts.name: SLAB-Mr.Thomas
posts.cooked:
Yes. This should create 100 different objects other than null

Sorry about XY-like . It is an existing contrived example that was easy with “myTimes” as long milliseconds but I decided to get-with-the-program and use Measure<Time> .

posts.name: Fletch
posts.cooked:
Heres an old docs link for Collections.fill() which might meet your needs.

https://docs.oracle.com/javase%2F7%2Fdocs%2Fapi%2F%2F/java/util/Collections.html#fill(java.util.List,%20T)

Caveat that I believe it would be all the same referenced object, so not as useful if you need mutability.

posts.name: SLAB-Mr.Thomas
posts.cooked: Thanks to @msoucy and @Fletch1373 for keeping me going on Measure . I was able to update my allwpilib PR Command-Based Best Practices Java examples to use Measure<Time> instead of long , etc. (Yes a beginner writing best-practices does seem a bit perverse but I tested the program and it works. Someone here encouraged me to use Measure so I did.)

posts.name: Kyle Reeve
posts.cooked:
SLAB-Mr.Thomas:

Looks like you solved it later on, but for charity: measures can’t be instantiated like that. Need to use one of the factories, like Seconds.of(I) .
